climate scientists are realised, and the planet's average temperature rises by 5C, the red breasted goose would lose 99% of its nesting places.  <P>Governments are under pressure to limit discharges of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases, which fuel global warming. Ute Collier, of WWF's climate change programme, said: \"Birds do not have political boundaries, they are global, breeding in the Arctic and migrating elsewhere.\"  <P>There are about 10,000 species of birds. About 1,000 of these are at risk of extinction   already. So far, most concern has been about temperate and tropical forest birds. But the Arctic is sensitive to any climate change, and many predictions of global warming expect temperature rises in the sub-Arctic regions to be much greater than in the tropics.  <P>Winter is in retreat. The growing season in Europe is 11 days longer than it was 35 years ago. Sea levels have crept higher throughout the century. Six of the 10 warmest years ever recorded occurred in the 1990s; the other four all happened in the late 1980s.  <P>Arctic birds are vulnerable even when their breeding conditions improve. With an earlier spring and higher June temperatures, they could do well and so could trees moving up from the south. But the following year, with more birds competing for fewer nesting spaces, robust species would survive while others perished. The study predicts the spoon-billed sandpiper, which numbers only up to about 2,800, will lose 56% of its habitat.  <P>Dr Collier said: \"There is still a lot we can do. If we get emissions down in the next 20 to 30 years, we will probably only see about half the increase in these temperatures. Species can adapt to slow change. It is an important message.\"","headline":"Warmer Arctic puts 12m birds under threat","trailText":"Five million geese and 7.5m sandpipers and other wading birds are threatened by global warming in the Arctic, a report warns today . ","newspaperPageNumber":"9","shouldHideAdverts":"false","pub